## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement + ThreadAbortException/ResetAbort as control flow.

### Why this breaks on .NET 6+

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime no longer supports preemptive thread termination. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone (`SYSLIB0006`).

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### What changed and why

| Old (.NET Framework) | New (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run()` | Uses thread pool; avoids manual thread management |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(token)` | Cancellation-aware waiting (.NET 6+ API) |
| `thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` | Cooperative cancellation replaces forced abort |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed | No equivalent needed — cancellation is cooperative |

### Key pitfalls for this migration

1. **Work must cooperate.** If `work()` is a long-running CPU-bound call that never checks the token, cancellation won't interrupt it — it will run to completion. To fix this, refactor `work` to accept a `CancellationToken` and check it at regular intervals:

   ```csharp
   public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
   {
       using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
       var token = cts.Token;
       var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
       // ... same as above
   }
   ```

2. **`CancellationTokenSource` must be disposed.** It holds timer resources when created with a timeout. Always use `using`.

3. **Blocking I/O won't be interrupted.** If `work()` blocks on `Thread.Sleep`, `socket.Read`, etc., the token has no effect. Replace with async alternatives (`Task.Delay(ms, token)`, `stream.ReadAsync(..., token)`).

4. **Truly uncooperative code** (third-party libs, native calls) cannot be cancelled with tokens. The only reliable fallback is to run the work in a **separate process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout.

5. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** — the `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures we only catch our own timeout, not an unrelated cancellation.
